  "prompt": "Why does a concussion cause someone to throw up?",
  "response": "A concussion, which is a type of traumatic brain injury, can cause a person to throw up due to several reasons:\n\n1. **Brain Impact:** The trauma can cause the brain to impact the inside of the skull. This can lead to the disruption of normal brain function including areas responsible for nausea and vomiting.\n\n2. **Increased Intracranial Pressure:** The injury can cause swelling or increased pressure inside the skull. This pressure can stimulate the area of the brain known as the vomiting center, located in the medulla oblongata.\n\n3. **Disruption of Autonomic Functions:** Concussions can affect the autonomic nervous system, which controls involuntary bodily functions. This disruption can lead to gastrointestinal upset and vomiting.\n\n4. **Vestibular System Impact:** If the concussion affects the vestibular system (which helps control balance and coordination), it can cause dizziness and vertigo, leading to nausea and vomiting.\n\n5. **Chemical Changes:** Trauma can cause the release of certain chemicals within the brain that can lead to nausea and vomiting.\n\nIf someone experiences vomiting after a head injury, it's important to seek medical attention, as it could be a sign of a serious concussion or other complications.",
